    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1952-02-01T17:08:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1952-02-01T17:08:00-05:00" n="23"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d23">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">795.00/2–252: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Joint Chiefs of Staff</gloss> to the
                        Commander in Chief, Far East (<persName corresp="#p_RGMB1" type="to"
                            >Ridgway</persName>)</hi>
                    <note n="1" xml:id="d23fn1">This telegram was prepared in the Department of
                        State by <gloss target="#t_UNP1">UNP</gloss> and approved by <persName
                            corresp="#p_JUA1">Johnson</persName> and <persName corresp="#p_MHF1"
                            >Matthews</persName> on Jan. 31; see the memorandum by <persName
                            corresp="#p_JUA1">Johnson</persName> to <persName corresp="#p_MHF1"
                            >Matthews</persName>, Jan. 31, 1952, enclosing a draft, in <gloss
                            target="#t_FE1">FE</gloss> files, lot 55 D 128, tab 122.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">top secret<lb/>priority</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1952-02-01T17:08:00-05:00"
                            >February 1, 1952—5:08 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <gloss target="#t_JCS1">JCS</gloss> 900075. From <gloss target="#t_JCS1"
                        >JCS</gloss>. Reur CX 62465.<note n="2" xml:id="d23fn2">
                        <hi rend="italic">
                            <ref target="#d23">Supra</ref>
                        </hi>.</note>
                </p>
                <list>
                    <label>1.</label>
                    <item>It is desirable to avoid naming any govts or authorities in recommendation
                        under item 5. Your del should indicate that it is not for mil cdrs to
                        determine what countries or authorities are in fact concerned in a polit
                        solution for Korea. It would be preferred, therefore, likewise to have no
                        mention of UN or <gloss target="#t_ROK1">ROK</gloss> in order to forestall a
                        Communist proposal to mention Peiping, <gloss target="#t_NK1">NK</gloss> or
                        USSR.</item>
                    <label>2.</label>
                    <item>If, however, it should become necessary to deal with question of who are
                        govts or authorities concerned, there would be no objection to indicating
                        that recommendation is addressed to North Korean and Peiping regimes, as
                        well as others, provided nature of recommendation foll lines indicated in
                        part V, <gloss target="#t_JCS1">JCS</gloss> 90083.<note n="3"
                            xml:id="d23fn3">For text, see <ref target="frus1951v07p1#pg_1377">
                                <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1951, vol. <hi
                                    rend="smallcaps">vii</hi>, Part 1, p. 1377</ref>.</note> In
                        other words, there is no objection to having a recommendation addressed to
                        UN organization, to mbr states, to <gloss target="#t_ROK1">ROK</gloss>,
                        Peiping, <gloss target="#t_NK1">NK</gloss>, that they cooperate in early
                        steps to deal at polit level with matters not settled by armistice. If
                        question of Soviet Union arises, you should indicate Soviet Union is mbr of
                        UN and as such recommendation is of course addressed to it as well.</item>
                    <label>3.</label>
                    <item>It is important, however, in view of State Dept tel [<gloss
                            target="#t_Gadel1">Gadel</gloss>] 393,<note n="4" xml:id="d23fn4">For
                            text, see <ref target="frus1951v07p1#pg_1282">
                                <hi rend="italic">ibid.</hi>, p. 1282</ref>.</note> not to commit
                        yourself to a polit conference, or polit discussions in any particular form,
                        or with particular participants.</item>
                    <label>4.</label>
                    <item>There is no objection to suggestion in para B, part 2.</item>
                </list>
            </div>
        </body>
